# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: billy-southworth
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The **1913 major league baseball season** began on April 9, 1913.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 5, with the New York Giants and Philadelphia Athletics as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the tenth World Series on October 7 and ended with Game 5 on October 11.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] In the third iteration of this World Series matchup, the Athletics defeated the Giants, four games to one, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1911.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Boston Red Sox from the 1912 season.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] This was the third of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each league.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Trolley Dodgers shortened its name to the Brooklyn Dodgers and the New York Highlanders renamed as the New York Yankees.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The 1913 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 9 with a game between the Philadelphia Phillies and Brooklyn Dodgers, while American League Opening Day took place the following day, with all AL teams but the Chicago White Sox and Cleveland Naps, playing.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 5.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 7 and October 11.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The National League ruled that umpires could no longer scout for teams, as was the case when Umpire Cy Rigler was being paid $2,200 (equivalent to $71,700 in 2025) by the Philadelphia Phillies for his role in having the team sign a pitcher, Eppa Rixey.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] 21 tie games (5 in AL, 16 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 7 and ended on October 11 with the Philadelphia Athletics defeating the New York Giants in the 1913 World Series in five games.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The 1913 season saw two teams move to two venues.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox renamed White Sox Park to Comiskey Park, named after team owner Charles Comiskey.
[src:billy-southworth/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Braves play two doubleheaders on April 19 and May 30 at the home of the Boston Red Sox at Fenway Park to accommodate large crowds.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The **1915 major league baseball season** began on April 10, 1915.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League regular season ended on October 3, and saw the Chicago Whales winning the Federal League pennant.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season for the National League and American League ended on October 7, with the Philadelphia Phillies and Boston Red Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 12th World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 5 on October 13.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox defeated the Phillies, four games to one, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1912.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Boston Braves from the 1914 season.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series had again featured the cities of Boston and Philadelphia, though this time with their opposite-league counterparts.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Hoosiers relocated to Newark, New Jersey as the Newark Peppers.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Buffeds, Chicago Federals, and Cleveland Naps renamed as the Buffalo Blues, Chicago Whales, and Cleveland Indians, respectively.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League brought an antitrust lawsuit against the National and American Leagues prior to the 1915 season.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The parties eventually reached a settlement and the Federal League disbanded after the season.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The major-league status of the Federal League was confirmed by the Special Baseball Records Committee (as convened by then-Commissioner of Baseball William Eckert) in 1969.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The 1915 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League, National League, and Federal League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season, and which lasted until the 140-game schedule of 1919.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Most teams played more than 154 games, due to tie games (called on account of darkness or weather) that had to be replayed; tie games are excluded from team standings, but the statistics of individual players are included in their season totals.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had its Opening Day on April 10, featuring all eight teams.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day for the American and National Leagues was on April 14, featuring the 16 teams of those two leagues, as had been scheduled the season prior.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had the final day of its regular season on October 3.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season for the National and American Leagues was October 7.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 13.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The National League established that player-managers would count against the player limit, so the bench manager would be unable to insert himself in any game during the season without forfeiting the right to carry one of the players on his roster.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The penalty for violating the rule was forfeiture of the game.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] 31 tie games (10 in AL, 13 in NL, 8 in FL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the Philadelphia Phillies in the 1915 World Series in five games.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The National and American Leagues refused a postseason against the Federal League.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Note: Attendance data for Federal League teams is unavailable.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] With the relocation of the Indianapolis Hoosiers from Indianapolis, Indiana to Newark, New Jersey as the Newark Peppers, they leave Federal League Park and move into Harrison Park.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Braves would play their last game at Fenway Park on July 26, having shared the park with the Boston Red Sox since the middle of 1914, and opened Braves Field on August 18, playing their final 26 of 78 home games and where they would go on to play for 38 seasons through 1952.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs would play their final game at West Side Park on October 3 against the St.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the home of the Chicago Whales (who would fold before the 1916 season), Weeghman Park for the start of the 1916 season.
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] For games 3 and 4 of the World Series, the Boston Red Sox use the Boston Braves home of Braves Field due to its larger capacity over their home at Fenway Park (40,000 to 27,000).
[src:billy-southworth/1915-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first year in a row where a World Series winning Red Sox used Braves Field.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The **1918 major league baseball season** began on April 15, 1918.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended earlier than originally scheduled, September 2, because of a reduced schedule due to American participation in World War I.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American League champions were the Chicago Cubs and Boston Red Sox, respectively.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 15th World Series on September 5 and ended with Game 6 on September 11.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox defeated the Cubs, four games to two, capturing their fifth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1916.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Chicago White Sox from the 1917 season.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day took place on April 15 with four American League teams playing, the Philadelphia Athletics at Boston Red Sox, and the New York Yankees at Washington Senators, while National League Opening Day saw all eight teams play the following day.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] It was the first season since 1906 which saw the two leagues open on different days.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] With World War I ongoing, a "work or fight" mandate was issued by the government, requiring men with non-essential jobs to enlist or take war-related jobs by July 1, or else risk being drafted.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] Baker granted an extension to MLB players through Labor Day, September 2.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] In early August, MLB clubs decided that the regular season would end at that time.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] As a result, the number of regular-season games that each team played varied—123 to 130 for AL teams and 124 to 131 for NL teams, including ties—reduced from their original 154-game schedules.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season would see all teams but the Cleveland Indians and St.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] Later in August, Baker granted a further extension to allow for the World Series to be contested; it began on September 5 and ended on September 11.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] World War I would end two months later, with the Armistice of 11 November 1918.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] 10 tie games (6 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 5 and ended on September 11 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the Chicago Cubs in the 1918 World Series in six games.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals is gradually referred to as Cardinal Field, after Helene Britton, daughter of the deceased former owner Frank Robison, sells her interest in the team following a deal in March 1917, ending the association between the Cardinals and the Robison family.
[src:billy-southworth/1918-major-league-baseball-season] By 1918, Cardinal Field became the name widely used.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The **1920 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1920.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 3, with the Brooklyn Robins and Cleveland Indians as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 17th World Series on October 5 and ended with Game 7 on October 12.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The Indians defeated the Robins, five games to two, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Cincinnati Reds from the 1919 season.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] This was the final season to be presided over by the three-person National Baseball Commission, which ran the major and minor leagues—composed of the American League President, National League President, and one team owner as president.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] In the wake of the Black Sox scandal, the credibility of baseball had been tarnished with the public and fans and the owners of the teams clamored for credibility to be restored.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The owners felt that creating one position with near-unlimited authority was the answer.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] After the season, the commission was replaced with the newly created office of Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Persisting rumors of the Chicago White Sox throwing the previous year's World Series to the Cincinnati Reds and another game during the 1920 season led to the game's brass looking for ways of dealing with the problems of gambling within the sport.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] At the time, MLB was governed by a three-man National Baseball Commission composed of American League President Ban Johnson, National League President John Heydler and Cincinnati Reds owner Garry Herrmann.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] At the request of the other owners, Herrmann left the office reducing the commission to be deadlocked by two.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] With the owners disliking one or both presidents, calls began for stronger leadership, although they opined they could support the continuation of the leagues' presidencies with a well-qualified Commissioner.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] A plan that began to circulate and gain support was dubbed the "Lasker Plan", after Albert Lasker, a shareholder of the Chicago Cubs, called for a three-man commission with no financial interest in baseball.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] With the Black Sox scandal exposed on September 30, 1920, Heydler began calling for the Lasker Plan.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] All eight NL teams supported the plan, along with three AL teams.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The three AL teams were the White Sox, the New York Yankees and the Boston Red Sox.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The teams in support of the Lasker Plan wanted federal judge Kenesaw Mountain Landis to take the office of Baseball Commissioner.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Johnson, who opposed the plan and thus, the appointment of Landis, had allies in the other five AL clubs, and attempted to get Minor League Baseball to side with him.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] However, the minor leagues would not, and when the AL teams learned their position, they relented and instead went along with the Lasker Plan.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The owners agreed that they needed a person with near-unlimited authority and a powerful person to fill the position of commissioner.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The owners approached Landis, who eventually accepted the position as the first Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] He drafted the agreement which gave him almost unlimited authority throughout the major and minor leagues – every owner on down to the batboys was accountable to the Commissioner – including barring owners from dismissing him, speaking critically of him in public or challenging him in court.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Landis also kept his job as a federal judge.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] As a result, the owners accepted the terms of the agreement with a scant trace of opposition, if any.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The 1920 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The 154-game format had previously been used since 1904, except for 1919, and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 with all but the Washington Senators and Boston Red Sox playing.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 3, with all teams but the Boston Red Sox and New York Yankees playing.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 5 and October 12.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The 1920 season featured an extremely rare tripleheader—the third in National League and major-league history, having previously occurred only in 1890 and 1896—when the Pittsburgh Pirates hosted the Cincinnati Reds on October 2 for three games, the day before the final day of the regular season.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The Reds won the first two games while the Pirates won the third game, which was called after six innings on account of darkness.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] After an August 31 game between the Philadelphia Phillies and Chicago Cubs, allegations began to arise that the game was fixed.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The state court in Chicago opened a grand jury to investigate gambling within baseball.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Gambler Billy Maharg came forward with information that he worked with New York gambler Arnold Rothstein and former boxer Abe Attell to get the White Sox to throw the 1919 World Series.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The White Sox again were contending for the American League title and were in a near-dead heat with the Cleveland Indians and New York Yankees.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] However, on September 28, eight White Sox players were indicted and suspended by owner Charlie Comiskey.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The Indians pulled ahead and won the pennant by two games over the White Sox.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (3 in AL, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 5 and ended on October 12 with the Cleveland Indians defeating the Brooklyn Robins in the 1920 World Series in seven games.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs' Weeghman Park is renamed to Cubs Park.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] By 1920, the name of Brush Stadium, home of the New York Giants and New York Yankees, fell into disuse, reverting to the Polo Grounds name.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals would play their last game at Cardinal Field on June 6, having played 28 seasons there going back to 1893, and returned to Sportsman's Park on July 1, having previously been their home venue for 11 season from 1882 to 1892, as well as the home of the St.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns since their relocation from Milwaukee, Wisconsin in 1902.
[src:billy-southworth/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The Cardinals would go on to play at Sportsman's Park for another 47 seasons through early 1966.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The **1921 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1921.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 2, with the New York Giants and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 18th World Series on October 5 and ended with Game 8 on October 13.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] In the first Subway Series World Series, the Giants defeated the Yankees, five games to three, capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1905.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Cleveland Indians from the 1920 season.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] 1921 was the first of three straight seasons in which the Yankees would lead the majors in wins.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Babe Ruth broke the single season home run record for the third consecutive season by hitting 59 home runs in 152 games.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Ruth also broke Roger Connor's record for the most home runs all time when he hit his 139th home run on July 18 against Bert Cole.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The record for career strikeouts, previously held by Cy Young was also broken in 1921 by Walter Johnson; Johnson led the league in strikeouts with 143 and ended the season with 2,835 strikeouts.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Young struck out 2,803 during his career.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds set a Major League record for the fewest strikeouts in a season, with only 308.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Future Hall of Famers Kiki Cuyler and Goose Goslin both debuted in September 1921.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The 1921 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 13 with all but the Chicago White Sox and Detroit Tigers playing.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 2.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 5 and October 13.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] 3 tie games (2 in AL, 1 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics had two tie games.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Tigers and Washington Senators had one tie game each.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 5 and ended on October 13 with the New York Giants defeating the New York Yankees in the 1921 World Series in eight games.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] On August 5, the Pittsburgh Pirates 8–5 victory over the Philadelphia Phillies at Forbes Field was the first Major League game to be broadcast on radio.
[src:billy-southworth/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Harold Arlin calls the game for Pittsburgh station KDKA.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The **1923 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1923.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 7, with the New York Giants and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 20th World Series on October 10 and ended with Game 6 on October 15.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] In the third consecutive iteration of the Subway Series, the Yankees defeated the Giants, four games to two, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] This was the third World Series between the two teams, and the first to see the Yankees win over the Giants.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Giants from the 1922 season.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second of eight seasons that "League Awards", a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), were issued.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] Only an American League award was given in 1923.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The 1923 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 17 with all teams playing, while American League Opening Day took place the following day with all teams playing.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 7.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 10 and October 15.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] 7 tie games (5 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 10 and ended on October 15 with the New York Yankees defeating the New York Giants in the 1923 World Series in six games.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Yankees leave the Polo Grounds, where they shared with the New York Giants for the previous 10 seasons, and open Yankee Stadium, where they would play for 84 seasons through 1973 and 1976 through 2008.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The Yankees, whose home had been Manhattan for their entire existence, moved into the Bronx where they remain to this day.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] Referring to the Philadelphia Phillies' home at National League Park, on July 11, *The Philadelphia Inquirer* coined the term Baker Bowl.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] "Baker Bowl" became a common name for the stadium until its closure in 1938, although the Phillies would still refer to the venue as its official "National League Park" name in newspaper advertisements.
[src:billy-southworth/1923-major-league-baseball-season] On August 21, Clark Griffith, owner of the Washington Senators since 1920, announced that National Park would be named after himself, Griffith Stadium.
[src:billy-southworth/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The **1924 major league baseball season** began on April 15, 1924.
[src:billy-southworth/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the New York Giants and Washington Senators as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:billy-southworth/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 21st World Series on October 4 and ended with Game 7 on October 10.
[src:billy-southworth/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The Senators defeated the Giants, four games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:billy-southworth/1924-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Yankees from the 1923 season.
[src:billy-southworth/1924-major-league-baseball-season] This was the third of eight seasons that "League Awards", a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), were issued.
[src:billy-southworth/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The 1924 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:billy-southworth/1924-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 15, featured all sixteen teams, for the first time since 1922.
[src:billy-southworth/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, while the American League would see its final day of the regular season the following day with a game between the Washington Senators and Boston Red Sox.
[src:billy-southworth/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 4 and October 10.
[src:billy-southworth/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 4 and ended on October 10 with the Washington Senators defeating the New York Giants in the 1924 World Series in seven games.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Late in life, Southworth served as a scout for the Braves.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He endured a great deal of tragedy in his baseball career, first experiencing the stillbirth of his twin babies and the deaths of his wife and his adult son.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 2008.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Six years later, the Cardinals inducted him into the St.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He also belongs to the Alabama Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth had a son, Billy Southworth Jr., and a cousin, Bill Southworth, who both played professional baseball.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth was born in Harvard, Nebraska, to Orlando and Mariah Southworth and raised in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He had four older brothers who played baseball.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Before he was old enough to play with them, Southworth would give his old socks to his brothers so they could create makeshift balls.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth decided to play baseball against his father's wishes.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Orlando Southworth had wanted his son to attend college.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] At the age of 19, he signed a contract with the Portsmouth Cobblers team in the Ohio State League.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He joined the Cleveland Indians in 1913, but only appeared in one game, entering as a replacement on defense.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] In 1914, Southworth married Lida Brooks.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] She was a minister's daughter and they had met while Southworth was playing for Portsmouth.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] The couple's son, William Brooks Southworth, was born during Southworth's early playing career.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Billy Southworth Jr. later became a professional baseball player for several seasons.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] The elder Southworth returned to the Cleveland Indians in 1915 and appeared in 60 games.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He played for the Birmingham Barons in 1917 and part of 1918, when he made the Pittsburgh Pirates and played in 64 major league games.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth played more regularly in 1919, appearing in 121 games and leading the league with 14 triples.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] With the exception of two seasons, Southworth played in at least that many games through 1926.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] In 1926, Southworth's offensive production increased and he finished the season with a .320 batting average, 16 home runs and 99 RBI.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He ran into difficulty with New York manager John McGraw that year, as Southworth's independent style became incompatible with McGraw's strict leadership.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He was traded from the New York Giants to the St.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Louis Cardinals in the middle of the season.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth suffered a 1927 rib injury that limited his playing time.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] The Cardinals' leadership began to look for a role for Southworth beyond his playing career.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth's managerial career began in 1928 with the Rochester Red Wings of the AA International League (IL), the top club in the Cardinals' farm system.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] In May, Southworth and his wife experienced the stillbirths of twins.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth returned home after losing the twins, but he quickly came back to Rochester.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Late in the season, Southworth received word that Billy Jr. had been accidentally shot by a neighbor in Columbus.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] His son recovered, but the experience shook the manager.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] The team won the IL championship that season.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Louis as player-manager for 1929, replacing Bill McKechnie, who won a National League pennant in 1928 and lost the World Series in four straight games to the New York Yankees.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth's Major League playing career reached the end of the road, as he appeared in only 19 games, five in the outfield, and batted only .188 with six hits.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He finished with a .297 batting average in 1,192 MLB games played, with 52 home runs, 91 triples, 173 doubles, 661 runs scored, and 561 RBI.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He stole 138 bases in his career and had double-digit steal totals in eight seasons.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] As a big leaguer, Southworth had 1,296 hits in 4,359 at bats.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] His 1929 MLB managerial debut was not much more successful than his playing stint.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Only one year removed from being a teammate of his charges, he attempted to impose discipline on the Cardinals, banning them from driving their own automobiles.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] The team did not respond to his hard line and won only 43 of their first 88 games.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth was sent back to Rochester on July 21, McKechnie was rehired, and the Cardinals finished in fourth place.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Although Southworth immediately resumed his successful minor league managerial career, the firing and personal tragedy — the death of his wife Lida at age 42 — began a downward spiral.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Beset by struggles with alcoholism, he quit a coaching job with the 1933 Giants during spring training and left baseball for two seasons.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] After a recovery, he rejoined the Cardinals' minor league system in 1935 and by 1939 he was again enjoying success as Rochester's manager.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He remarried in 1935, wedding the former Mabel Stemen, with whom he had a daughter.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] In June 1940, he received a second chance with the struggling Cardinals when owner Sam Breadon fired manager Ray Blades and promoted Southworth from Rochester.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] This time, the Cards flourished under him.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] With talented players such as Enos Slaughter, Marty Marion, Stan Musial, Walker Cooper, Mort Cooper, Whitey Kurowski and Johnny Beazley being harvested each spring from the club's farm system, the Cardinals entered a Golden Age in their history.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Upon Southworth's appointment, they won 69 of 109 games and jumped from seventh to third place in 1940.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] The following season they won 97 games and finished second.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] From 1942 to 1944, the Cardinals won 106, 105 and 105 games, three pennants and two World Series titles.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth was the first manager to lead a team to 100 wins in three consecutive seasons.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] His 1942 Cardinals, who breezed to the World Series championship in five games, were the only team (out of eight) to ever defeat Joe McCarthy's New York Yankees in a Fall Classic.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] In 1943, both teams met again in the World Series; but this time, the Yankees turned the tables on the Redbirds, winning in five games.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] The Cards' third successive National League pennant, in 1944, produced another world championship, a six-game triumph over the American League (AL) St.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] With it, Southworth had presided over one of the most dominant three-year stretches in National League (NL) history.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] However, another personal family tragedy struck when on February 15, 1945, his son, Billy Jr., by then a United States Army Air Forces major, died when his Boeing B-29 Superfortress crashed into Flushing Bay, New York after taking off from Mitchel Field, New York, on a training flight to Florida.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Still, Southworth began managing at the beginning of the 1945 season, which saw his Cardinals win 95 games but finish second, three games behind the Chicago Cubs.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth moved to the Boston Braves in 1946, signing a then-lucrative managing contract for a reported $50,000 per season, and immediately led the Braves into the first division.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Talented pitchers Johnny Sain and Warren Spahn had both returned from service in World War II that year.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] In 1948, the Braves won their second NL pennant of the 20th century—and Boston's last National League title—but were defeated in six games by the Cleveland Indians in the 1948 World Series.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] In that World Series, all of the games were close except for one, when the Braves beat pitcher Bob Feller 11–5.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Author John Rossi writes that Sain lost some respect for Southworth after the manager said that managing and not talent had won the 1948 pennant.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Sain had already become irritated with Southworth after the 1948 signing of unproven "bonus baby" pitcher Johnny Antonelli.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Sain and Southworth rarely spoke after 1948.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] During the following season, 1949, Boston struggled on the field and was in chaos off the diamond.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth was rumored to be drinking heavily and near nervous collapse.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Some players complained about his rules and regulations, and some, including starting shortstop Alvin Dark and second baseman Eddie Stanky, were critical of his drinking.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Meanwhile, others, like Sain, resented the amount of credit Southworth had received for the 1948 pennant.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] With Boston at 55–54 on August 16, Southworth turned the Braves over to coach Johnny Cooney for the remainder of 1949.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] A newspaper account at the time characterized the change as a leave of absence for health reasons.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] With Cooney, the Braves finished fourth.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] A finish that high in the standings guaranteed the team shares of the World Series money, but the Braves players voted to only give Southworth a quarter share.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] After some of the rebellious players (including Dark and Stanky) had been traded, Southworth returned to his post in 1950 and led the Braves to a fourth-place finish.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] On August 29, 1950, Southworth recorded his 1,000th win as manager, leading the Braves to a 4–0 win over Cincinnati.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth had managed to convert a team that hadn't finished fourth since 1934 into one that would finish fourth or better for six straight seasons.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] However, an aging team and declining attendance would bode poorly for both Southworth's career and the Braves' future in New England.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] In 1951, Southworth's club was only 28–31 on June 19.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He called the team's general manager, John Quinn, and asked to be allowed to resign, and he was replaced by his former standout right fielder, Tommy Holmes (he would finish out the season but was fired in the middle of what turned out to be the final season of the Braves in Boston).
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth's major league managerial win–loss record was 1,044–704–22.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] His .597 winning percentage is seventh all-time among managers to McCarthy's .615.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth has the fewest games managed (1,770) for any manager to have won 1,000 games.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth was the first to win the World Series as a player and again as a manager.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth remained with the Braves as a scout in the 1950s.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He was acquitted of drunken driving charges after a 1955 arrest, and retired from scouting at the end of his contract following the 1956 season.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] During his scouting days, he signed future all-time home run leader Hank Aaron, who was playing for the Indianapolis Clowns of the Negro leagues.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] For the last couple of decades of his life, Southworth lived outside of Sunbury, Ohio.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] By the summer of 1969, his health had begun to fail and he was confined to his home.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He gave a final interview to a reporter for the *St.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Louis Post-Dispatch*; he commented on how difficult it would be for the 1969 Cardinals to win a third straight National League championship, as the 1944 team had done.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Though he had quit smoking many years earlier, Southworth died of emphysema that year in Columbus, Ohio, and was buried in Green Lawn Cemetery.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth's cousin, Bill Southworth, appeared in the major leagues in 1964.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Dark recalled that Southworth was a "mild" person who wanted everyone to like him.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He preferred to let his players play according to their respective styles, rather than micro-managing their every moves.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in 2008.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He had been eligible for election as a player in the 1940s, but he received few votes.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] After Southworth had been left off of the ballot as a manager in 2003, author Raymond Mileur had begun a campaign of letter writing, phone calls to the Hall of Fame, radio show comments and advocacy through his website known as "The Birdhouse".
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Southworth was elected after receiving 13 votes from the 16-member Veterans Committee.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] On the occasion of Southworth's election to the Hall of Fame, one of his former players on the 1948 Braves, Clint Conatser, paid tribute to his old manager.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] "He just had a gut feeling about the right thing to do in a situation", Conatser recalled.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] "The moves he would make would work for him — all the time, not occasionally.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] It's like some guys can pick horses out of nowhere.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] In January 2014, the Cardinals announced that Southworth was among 22 former players and personnel to be inducted into the St.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] Louis Cardinals Hall of Fame Museum for the inaugural class of 2014.
[src:billy-southworth/billy-southworth] He is also a member of the Alabama Sports Hall of Fame.
